"The Doctor of The Rights of the Porras" he seems to remember that Petr Hulínsk obtained his doctorate in law from the Bratislava police academy.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches," as published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They tend to be old, they can't work, for example, for health reasons, they're single and they don't have children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such a thing."
"Healthy young women are also not ingested because they assist in work and have children," explains a nun who, in the west African state capital Burkina Faso, is in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch-hunt.
However, this has a catch.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can't read," Die Standard warns of the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, a neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a wretched cluster of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman ignites in the oil that is used for ritual ations.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expel evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: "The devourers of human souls always poseed a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease witch-hunt, the president still participated in it in The Gambia last year.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a wide-rant witch hunt that had supposedly been related to his death and had tried to kill the president himself through black magic."
"To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forsaever, took randomly chosen men and women among gambian peoples to the president's property in Kanilai," Amnesty International notes in its report.
On the farm, people arrested had to drink an herb potion with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, around a thousand detainees were finally released.
Bakala's tenant: warms up with charcoal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, of old and reluctant, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zde-ek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving a sentence.
All three of them have just been caught liberalizing rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 kronor for a two-room apartment with separate second-rate kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains, half-angry, half-resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which rated the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing them on how to proceed in these cases.
But in the face of this, man only makes one ademan.
"Everyone says one thing, " he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large liberalisation testing laboratory.
After New Year will occur with the vast majority of flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rental.
That's why Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "lab" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of Ostrava's four and, on Tuesday at nine o'clock, it was already full.
Right next to the gates are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up a number.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
Pressing it exits the machine with a small paper with a number.
It hardly gives time to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple comes to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the old days: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar issues.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava at the tenants' mailboxes of most of the 44,000 RPG-owned flats around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes on the cards an increase in the rent of between 15 and 38%.
A special window opens at the customer service center for new rentals on November 18.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting," the workers in it briefly respond when the client shows up as a journalist.
Bakala's liberalization and old miners' flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already dealt with loudly and clearly by the Vice-President of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the SSD, and now they are continuously featured in newspapers in the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
They didn't even change my bathroom dish, the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, for the moment more than anything retirees come to check if they receive a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special RPG offer.
Half of the February rent discount will also be received by the remaining tenants who sign the new contract by December 15.
However, the mining "liberalization" window certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubt.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about forty or fifty people about the rent in 2011," says the window clerk.
In the meantime, RPG proposes on the web and on its planks to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If both parties do not reach an agreement on rent, an independent judge must resolve the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and fully in accordance with the law," RPG warns on its pages.
"Nobody's going to be judged here," says one of RPG Byty's employees, and a man on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5, 000 left for the meal; I don't have the means to go to court," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"Current rents still do not even cover the amounts needed to maintain the community fund," recalls Pavel Klime, director of RPG Byty's residential portfolio, adding that the sloppy state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG it was able with rentals to invest in apartments four billion, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some details highlighting in red.
"The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, or more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square meter per month," it is indicated on the screen.
I only increase the 400-story rental of the RPG portfolio by 38%.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 kronor per square meter," RPG says.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale from four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see chart) back on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people who sign the rent increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of the employees of the Arch.Design.
The architectural projects company Arch.Design, whose studio included numerous well-known buildings of Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
Around 90 people work at the company, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and liners to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offer to its workers within the framework of its social program.
Builders and architectes in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, managed to secure funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an endowment of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design is required to keep the mini-guards running with their own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and economy rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified personnel; In addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for care. The nursery currently welcomes children without an age limit, although most of them are under the age of three.
Since it is a "mini-guard", it can only simultaneously accommodate a maximum of five children, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-guard program are comparable to the usual preschool education program.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school readiness, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
Not surprisingly, this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs are reminiscent of a dinosaur's spine and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of her skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it "the house of bones."
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, you can see a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
It winds and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us inside as well.
Wavy wood copies window frames, railings, door ornaments, peepholes and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
Reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project came ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and the Park of Guell, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic shape, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motifs.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange to tilt forty-five degrees.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the building standards of the time at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so impacted with the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
He resented, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: just a fortnight after the request of the town hall, Josep Batlló applied (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors was installed the owner himself.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without being renounced to the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the Unesco World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded visits to the common area and attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not negligible, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
