A finger index longer than the ring indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest rate than annular are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger may be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, As Indicated by Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, it monitored more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, at the same time, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the indica finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They had the same chances of prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were the same length.
For men with a longer rate than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under the age of 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer rate.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pas, told TK that he knows the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "fully demonstrated".
