Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private companies.
Crime raises greater concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinbarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it allows to track changes in attitude in the region.
The results of this year's september and early October survey highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively lively humor prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in a number of countries on South America's Pacific coast (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a small 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
He also grew up in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a sharp decline in production last year.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44% of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than the 25% recorded in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% said they trusted their country's Congress and 45% in their government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it occurred during the global financial crisis is likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were affected only by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Moreover, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year to 32%.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
Such sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the polls began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31% say that, whether they or a close relative, they have been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has fallen since 38% last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic yields are reflected in greater support for private companies and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say that private companies are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56% (see Figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% support private companies), although their leftist president, Hugo Chavez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% vs. 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
