A more moderate side of China's peacekeeping is promoted
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the passage in a city square, harshly inspecting the nervous people in his care, issuing orders quietly with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, the burly policemen of China's urban order, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and inclination to violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firm!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "What are pretty girls like!"
Four girls who barely spent their teenage years in identical white gloves and olive green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
"Personally, I think they look normal, " said Mr Tang, dismissingly.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have an undergraduate degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to one report, 50 officers surrounded a discolous snacks cart, and watched him frowning constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the police cough a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's small respect for these city squadrons.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are authorized only to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news outlet routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, hubei Province inspectors beat dead a passerby after using his cell phone to film them while disbanding a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published online, describing how to effectively whip criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a shanghai watermelon street vendor suffered brain damage after a quarrel with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government," lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really meticulous clean-up."
Skeptics say the current approach is a long way from this.
After the district applied through a notice for eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered whether women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district's ad called for female candidates from 18 to 22 years old, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features."
They had to have an above-average height of 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
Withdrawal at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials said the work was physically too hard for women over the age of 25.
"His image is the important thing," an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes the temperament "and the inner qualities".
Female chengguans are like vases, she said, adding, "in addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities."
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city administration office, is not eager to support that description.
But he noted that height demands were standard in many Chinese work notices for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
If this means being handsome, it's a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the disabled or disfigured should not present himself.
"We can't let a lame person or a hunchback come to work here," Mr. Zheng said.
"His image wouldn't be right."
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with his red cheeks and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn't think the accent on her appearance is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" he asked with a sardonic look.
His dimpled co-worker, Xu Yang, 21, said "Our work must present the image of the city."
They also don't object to their time-bound work, they said, because they harbor bigger career ambitions than just driving away vendors in the alleys where they're supposed to confine their business.
Each morning, the squad faces about a dozen street vendors who throw themselves on foot or by bike, trying to sell as many rolls or tofu bowls as possible before being thrown out.
"Mr. Wang, you have to go."
"We've told her many times!" said Miss Xu as a saleswoman escaped on foot, temporarily abandoning her bike cart with side dishes of noodles.
Officers describe their duties as more monotonous than exhausting.
"This is about the same every day," said Huang Jing, 20, who studies marketing in his spare hours.
"Very routine".
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate the goods of the vendors.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
This tends to protect them from sudden public demonstrations of animosity against bureaucracy, which are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, Yunnan's provincial capital, mutinyed after the false rumor spread that Chengguan officers had killed a salesman.
More than a dozen chengguan police officers were injured in the night episode; 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
For the time being Xindu has prevented such violence.
