Can civics build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, a little civics have been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders made no progress on the major issues that need to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences of the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the president's deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the remaining political differences among members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are on a period of trial, begging each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for renewed partisan warfare.
Which is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent evaluations of it by participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too great and too deeply entrenched to suggest any rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, expenses, healthcare or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse party passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefit to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new STRATEGIC Arms Reduction Treaty (START) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112nd. Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement would begin.
"After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will revert the situation to a confrontational one," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civics can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the main event of 2012," he said.
The motives have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the tea party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As aware as Republican leaders are about the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to fulfill their promises to cut state spending and override the new health law.
These supporting lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and increasing some taxes and retirement age, and spending cuts.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, by their own assessment, have forging the issue of deficits on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected on the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there are at least currently little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between White House Republicans and Congressional Republicans.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes, and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would bring about change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a slash, as happened in 1995, then both parties will look closely at people's reaction.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partisanship and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
