Red Bull triumphs in F1 with a secret Siemens weapon
A software designs improvements in cars in real time.
Since Red Bull broke into the formula one world in 2004, his story in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into account the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of the last few seasons, last November, in the final stretch of the championship all bet on the triumph of Fernando Alonso's Ferrari.
Without detracting from the skill as a driver of the final champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor the ability of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the formula world has become a legend the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to turn it into a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from high automotive competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to design assembly chains of manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding failures and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula One factory has enabled Red Bull to design and implement "in a few hours, almost real time", the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during racing and testing.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications to the cars.
Siemens' manager explained that PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull's carbies with the exception of the engine, which is Renault's sole responsibility.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be brought from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological improvement is the $40 million figure that each Formula One team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its carids in a location about 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happened there is considered "top secret".
The squad for this task is 580 people, including its two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull's Formula One hero is arguably recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, are other protagonists whose contest is invaluable and their zero notoriety.
The factory's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be said that R&amp;D advances in wagon cars brought 50% of the victories and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and the technology adds up to 85% of the success, while pilots contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computing as they "are unpredictable gladiators".
