Go ahead that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the ancient traditions of much of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to the transgressive countries, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defining for a long time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission stimulated deficits, the German government pulled a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans for fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece's rescue decision.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published one were very much against Greece's bailout.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding reform of the Union's treaties, in order to make possible the rescue of a country while forcing private lenders to take part in the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But your proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should be attending the Union reform process that will enable those measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he's telling us all that even if we now have to take measures that he may not very much agree with, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
