Sport and law enforcement
Tretas like Alonso and Ramos' in front of Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly released by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behaviour is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes to finish the match (which their team already clearly had won), the two players deliberately wasted time in pulling out foul paths to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will already finish as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the liguilla, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass card cleaners to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and the players involved with different financial amounts.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unintenritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen in the reported case is because it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts nobility and honor, and which has sometimes been fined to its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any event, the debate revolves around whether such behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions commit law enforcement; because, in fact, they are actions that are respectful of the sporting regulations, but they seem to avoid their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that sportsmanship comprises is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not jeopardized, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these goods referred to in fair play is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
However, the paradoxical thing about the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not add to what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders gain in the intentional mis faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the opponent is not disadvantaged or profited in the same match, as obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage obviously is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this performance the players play a penalty match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by card accumulation occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the present case, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the boundary between wit and law enforcement is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises by two factors: because it was two self-expressions and because of the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as it is aesthetic.
