Avengers hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandal at the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation that each record created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of public knowledge news is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unreleased research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who engage in occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, as is lazy (or has little craving) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Libération), who only considers what he can recognize true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the US embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the previous week.
So why have the revelations in these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of State can phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have been transformed into espionage centres.
Any viewer who watchs research films knows it perfectly, we just pretend we don't know it from hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad picture of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both victims and executioners.
But let's go into the true nature of what's happened.
In the past, in Orwell's day, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be put up with it that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without secrecy, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like posting it on a street sign.
But it is also clear that, with today's technologies, confidential conversations cannot be expected over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has traveled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a science fiction thing and therefore novel, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at best, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with (telephone) cables.
Video (analog) tapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now (digital) CDs only allow you to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the journeys involved, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the old world, the press was trying to understand what was secretly being plotted in embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: France's sloppy in its promises of funding
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked funding promises (called fast starts or early ones) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French sloppy ones have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union undertook to contribute EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that their commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major supplementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The operation transparency proved appreciable and appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has referred to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
In contrast, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while seeking to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the calculation method.
Some, such as France, consider that every euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Clearly, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to reducing emissions based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); refer to the EU document to see it in your own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments to 100% donations.
In other words, when most of the European Union contributes a euro to fulfil its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start funding, France does a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to stocks over time and, on the other hand, in relation to true financial effort.
Spending as little as 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The early financing chapter is relatively short-term in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could advance discussions on gambling in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We are therefore left with the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start-ups and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy one day ingests 81 different chemicals, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem addressed", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food usually consumed by a child of about ten years in four meals and one snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which respect official recommendations (five parts fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PEs), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"While virtually all cases do not exceed the legal limits for each of the chemicals individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to possibly carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is of concern," the association says.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, where the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, tests discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk of these "contaminant cocktails" to the consumer is "probably underestimated," the study says.
The European Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the seriousness of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.